{
  "texts": [
    "Simple graphs (Fig. 2a) are the most common type of network used in the literature.",
    "Examples of simple graphs include Zachary's Karate Club graph 27, Hetionet 19, and SPOKE 15.",
    "In these graphs, entities are represented as nodes, and edges are used to model relationships between them.",
    "These graphs usually lack formal semantics for the edges and nodes.",
    "Edges are often semantically overloaded, ignoring the distinction between data (e.g., a protein participating in a process) and metadata (e.g., the source of information about the protein's participation in that process)."
  ]
}